Admixture graph, gene flow, and selection analyses
==================================================

Plink code for data filtering steps for admixture graph and gene flow analyses:

    
    for i in {1..9}
    do
    # convert vcf into plink's binary format
    plink --vcf ../data/SNPs/scaffold_${i}.filter.snp.vcf.gz --set-missing-var-ids @:# --allow-extra-chr --biallelic-only strict --double-id --make-bed --out scaffold_${i}
    # get heterozygote frequencies for each site
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i} --allow-extra-chr --hardy --out scaffold_${i}
    # keep sites with observed heterozygosity less than 0.05
    awk '$7 < 0.05 {print $2}' scaffold_${i}.hwe > het_filt_${i}.snps
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i} --allow-extra-chr --extract het_filt_${i}.snps --make-bed --out scaffold_${i}_het
    # perform additional maf > 0.05 filter on het-filtered file
    # change to --maf 0.01 for SNPs for GRoSS selection analysis
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i}_het --allow-extra-chr --maf 0.05 --make-bed --out scaffold_${i}_het_maf
    
    # filter to keep unadmixed individuals along with geno filter
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i}_het_maf --allow-extra-chr --geno 0.1 --mac 1 --keep pops_to_keep.txt --make-bed --out scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno
    
    # two-step linkage pruning for maf > 0.05
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno --allow-extra-chr --indep-pairwise 10kb 1 0.8 --out ld1_unadmixed_maf_${i}
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno --allow-extra-chr --extract ld1_unadmixed_maf_${i}.prune.in --make-bed --out \
    scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno_10kb
    
    plink --bfile scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno_10kb --allow-extra-chr --indep-pairwise 50 1 0.8 --out ld2_unadmixed_maf_${i}
    plin    k --bfile scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno_10kb --allow-extra-chr --extract ld2_unadmixed_maf_${i}.prune.in --make-bed --out \
    scaffold_${i}_het_maf_geno_10kb_50
    
    done
    
    plink --merge-list het_maf_list.txt --allow-extra-chr --make-bed --out merged/foxtail_het_maf

    indivname:    foxtail_het_maf.fam
    outputformat:    PACKEDANCESTRYMAP
    genooutfilename:   foxtail_het_maf.geno
    snpoutfilename:    foxtail_het_maf.snp
    indoutfilename:    foxtail_het_maf.ind

    convertf -p het_maf/het_maf.parfile

After adding population labels to the third column of the .ind file, the PACKEDANCESTRYMAP format set of files was ready for import into R for use with the Admixtools package.

I used function in Admixtools, which are based on Patterson’s F-statistics, to look at population relationships and evidence of possible gene flow between them.

While the tool recommends a change point (indicating the appropriate number of migration edges) based on a default threshold, we selected the three-migration model based on when the model likelihood appears to plateau.

Selection analysis using GRoSS

Convert file to GRoSS format using GLACTOOLS (4pops\_to\_keep.txt contains the IDs for individuals from C1, C2, C3, and W1 (submitted as a job on an HPC):

    
    plink --bfile foxtail_het_maf0.01 --allow-extra-chr  --keep 4pops_to_keep.txt
    
    glactools vcfm2acf --onlyGT --fai Yugu1_nine.fa.fai 4pop.vcf.gz  | glactools meld -f ../smcpp/meta-pop.txt  -  |\
    glactools acf2gross --noroot - > 4pop.gross
    

Write admixture graph/tree topology in dot format:

    cat treeGross.dot

    digraph G {
    R -> W1 [ ] ;
    R -> ANC1 [ ] ;
    ANC1 -> C3 [ ] ;
    ANC1 -> ANC2 [ ] ;
    ANC2 -> C1 [ ] ;
    ANC2 -> C2 [ ] ;
    } 

Run GRoSS (submitted as a job on an HPC):

    
    Rscript GRoSS.R -e 4pop.gross -d treeGross.dot -o SNPstat_out.tsv
    

    library("tidyverse")
    library("reshape2")
    

The following code is adapted from an analysis template provided on the method’s github ([https://github.com/FerRacimo/GRoSS/blob/master/Plotting\_and\_Windowing.txt](https://github.com/FerRacimo/GRoSS/blob/master/Plotting_and_Windowing.txt)):

    
    table <- read.table("SNPstat_out.tsv",sep="",header=TRUE)
    
    
    
    # merge across 10 SNP windows with 5 SNP steps
    
    average <- c()
    for(chr in seq(1,9)){
    print(chr)
    onechr <- table[which(table[,1]==chr),]
    pvalpos <- which(mapply(grep,"Pval",colnames(onechr)) == 1)
    chipos <-  which(colnames(onechr) %in% colnames(onechr)[-c(pvalpos)][-c(1,2,3)])
    onechr <- as.data.frame(t(apply(onechr,1,function(row){row[pvalpos] <- -log10(row[pvalpos]); return(row)})))
    winsize <- 10
    winstep <- 5
    startvec <- seq(1,dim(onechr)[1]-winsize+1,winstep)
    endvec <- seq(winsize,dim(onechr)[1],winstep)
    winlims <- cbind(startvec,endvec)
    
    
    # AVERAGE CHI-SQUARED (10 SNPs)
    averagetemp <- as.data.frame(t(apply(winlims,1,function(window){     
    block <- onechr[seq(window[1],window[2]),]
    chisqstats <- block[,chipos]
    avgstats <- apply(chisqstats,2,mean)
    avgpval <- 1 - pchisq(avgstats,1)
    return(c(chr,onechr[window[1],2],onechr[window[2],3],avgstats,avgpval))
    })))
    colnames(averagetemp) <- colnames(onechr)
    average <- rbind(average,averagetemp)
    }

Getting -log10(pvalue) cutoff:

    (cutoff = quantile(c(-log10(melttab$Pvals)),
                           0.99999))
    

     99.999%
